
A shell script is a collection of commands written in a file that the Linux/Unix shell executes to automate system tasks like process management and system information retrieval.

1. Display top 10 processes in ascending order
	Processes in Linux can be viewed using the ps command.
	Sorting is done using sort.
	Ascending order means arranging values from smallest to largest (e.g., PID, CPU usage).
	head is used to limit output to the first 10 processes.

2. Display processes with highest memory usage
	Memory usage is shown using ps with %MEM.
	Processes are sorted in descending order to get highest memory usage.
	head displays top memory-consuming processes.

3. Display current logged-in user and log name
	whoami gives the current user.
	who shows all logged-in users.
	$LOGNAME or logname gives login name.

4. Display current shell, home directory, kernel version
	$SHELL → current shell
	$HOME → home directory
	uname -r → kernel version
    
---------------------------------------------

nano ascend.sh
#!/bin/bash

ps -eo pid,comm,%cpu,%mem --sort=%cpu | head -n10

chmod +x ascend.sh
./ascend.sh
-------------------------------

nano mem.sh
#!/bin/bash

ps -eo pid,comm,%cpu,%mem --sort=-%mem | head -n10

chmod +x mem.sh
./mem.sh
-------------------------------

nano user.sh
#!/bin/bash
echo "Current User:$(whoami)"
echo "Login Name:$(logname)"

chmod +x user.sh
./user.sh
-------------------------------

nano shell.sh
#!/bin/bash
echo "Current Shell: $SHELL"
echo "Home Directory: $HOME"
echo "Kernel Version:$(uname -r)"
chmod +x shell.sh
./shell.sh

